&gt;&gt; I'll ask the first question.

00:45:06.430 --> 00:45:07.730
&gt;&gt; J.R. Biersmith: Sure.

00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:09.030
&gt;&gt; What about their families?

00:45:09.030 --> 00:45:10.330
Their parents?

00:45:10.330 --> 00:45:11.630
Did you have to contact
their parents?

00:45:11.630 --> 00:45:12.930
&gt;&gt; J.R. Biersmith: Do you know

00:45:12.930 --> 00:45:14.230
that the young lady
behind you is not happy

00:45:14.230 --> 00:45:15.530
that you asked the first question?

00:45:15.530 --> 00:45:17.100 position:56%
Because she's the woman in the room.

00:45:17.100 --> 00:45:20.570
Say again about their families.

00:45:20.570 --> 00:45:22.250
What was the question?

00:45:22.250 --> 00:45:23.560
&gt;&gt; Were they aware of the movie?

00:45:23.560 --> 00:45:26.660
Were they involved
with making the movie?

00:45:26.660 --> 00:45:29.850
&gt;&gt; J.R. Biersmith: Yeah, so both
of -- yeah, Sa'ad and Saadiq,

00:45:29.850 --> 00:45:32.720
both Sa'ad and Saadiq, both of
their mothers are in the film.

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:34.330
I didn't interview the mothers.

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:38.210
I hired folks in Mogadishu to
do those interviews for me.

00:45:38.210 --> 00:45:41.610
When we went out to Sa'ad's
village to interview his mother,

00:45:41.610 --> 00:45:44.130
I wanted to do it myself,
but I couldn't.

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:47.320
Because of Sa'ad's prominence and
being from this small village,

00:45:47.320 --> 00:45:50.080
if a cameraman goes
with him to his village,

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:53.060
and you look like I
do, he stands out.

00:45:53.060 --> 00:45:54.440
It's like, "Oh, what are
those guys doing here?

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:56.530
What's the story they're
trying to tell?"

00:45:56.530 --> 00:46:00.440
So, we sent a guy that had
worked for Reuters from Nairobi,

00:46:00.440 --> 00:46:04.490
he went out to Sa'ad's village and
got the interview with his mother.

00:46:04.490 --> 00:46:07.910 position:56%
And there's a really powerful moment
in the film where she talks about --

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:11.730
he was born in 1993, five
months before Black Hawk Down.

00:46:11.730 --> 00:46:14.920
And it was just coming
off of the famine in 1992,

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:17.890
and so she was pregnant
during that time.

00:46:17.890 --> 00:46:23.030
And she said she'd go to the river
water, the Shebelle River to,

00:46:23.030 --> 00:46:25.480
just to get drink, you
know, to get anything

00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:27.240
and she had nothing to feed him.

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:30.070
So, like she couldn't
even produce breastmilk.

00:46:30.070 --> 00:46:38.620
So, to think about just being
born and surviving is, to me,

00:46:38.620 --> 00:46:41.630
is a statement in itself.

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:44.060
And now to think he's
in St. Louis trying

00:46:44.060 --> 00:46:48.820 position:56%
to navigate this complicated world,
complicated society that we live in,

00:46:48.820 --> 00:46:52.960
and that's what I think is
so, you know, I'm going more,

00:46:52.960 --> 00:46:56.870 position:56%
I'm expanding more on your question,
but I get excited about his journey,

00:46:56.870 --> 00:46:59.110
because I'm learning a lot as well.

00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:07.440
Like I've learned a lot about my
trajectory as an American citizen

00:47:07.440 --> 00:47:11.660
and what I expect from the world
because they're in my presence.

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:15.200
And when they're around you,
you get this sense of simplicity

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:17.030
and what matters, you know.

00:47:17.030 --> 00:47:19.120
And we make these busy schedules.

00:47:19.120 --> 00:47:21.150
And Sa'ad, for the life of him,

00:47:21.150 --> 00:47:23.960
cannot figure out why
everyone's so busy.

00:47:23.960 --> 00:47:26.830 position:56%
Like just why are you running around
all the time and so much stress

00:47:26.830 --> 00:47:29.190
and now you got these bills coming
from all these different places

00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:30.780
and -- you know, and
that complexity.

00:47:30.780 --> 00:47:34.100
Or Saadiq will say, "There's
a woman at the bus stop.

00:47:34.100 --> 00:47:35.700
Like why -- and it's raining.

00:47:35.700 --> 00:47:39.320
Why didn't anybody pick her up?"

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:41.860
We just drive, you know, like
we don't think about it anymore

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:43.160
like it's a feared thing.

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:45.090
We don't just pick somebody up
and set them in the car anymore.

00:47:45.090 --> 00:47:46.810
That doesn't happen.

00:47:46.810 --> 00:47:52.050
So how they challenge me to see
the community that I grew up in

00:47:52.050 --> 00:47:55.630
as a result of these mothers
that somehow got them raised

00:47:55.630 --> 00:47:58.960
and on their own two feet
is pretty remarkable to me.

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:00.890
Of course, I've worried
about both of their safety,

00:48:00.890 --> 00:48:04.750
both of the mothers, like anybody
that appears in the film I worry

00:48:04.750 --> 00:48:06.620
about on some small level.

00:48:06.620 --> 00:48:08.860
But I think, Sa'ad and
Saadiq were the, you know,

00:48:08.860 --> 00:48:10.630
they're the central
figures of the film.

00:48:10.630 --> 00:48:14.710
And they've both said that, and
this one is what breaks my heart,

00:48:14.710 --> 00:48:18.530
is that, you know, "Both of our
moms, like their journey was

00:48:18.530 --> 00:48:22.940
to raise us, and I
hope that they're okay,

00:48:22.940 --> 00:48:26.930
but they did what they
were supposed to do.

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:28.230
Like, they raised us."

00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:30.480
Like, that's what they're
most proud of.

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:32.340
And I don't know how to take that.

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:34.530
I don't know what that means.

00:48:34.530 --> 00:48:38.570
Other than, we hope
that they're okay.

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:41.150
And certainly, I do too.

00:48:41.150 --> 00:48:43.770
So, yes?

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:46.400
&gt;&gt; Well, I just wanted to
say thank you very much.

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:47.700
&gt;&gt; J.R. Biersmith: Thank you.

00:48:47.700 --> 00:48:54.590
&gt;&gt; And about two years ago, in
2014, you showed Scoring for Peace,

00:48:54.590 --> 00:49:00.180
which was a film about
the people in East Africa,

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:01.730
Burundi, [inaudible] and Uganda.

00:49:01.730 --> 00:49:05.280
And so the filmmaker donated
the film to the library,

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:09.960
and we hope that we'll
get Men in the Arena, too.

00:49:09.960 --> 00:49:14.880
But I also have a question,
and that is,

00:49:14.880 --> 00:49:16.180
as a journalist myself,
I know that doesn't pay.

00:49:16.180 --> 00:49:17.480
How did you fund this?

00:49:17.480 --> 00:49:18.780
All the travel --

00:49:18.780 --> 00:49:20.100
&gt;&gt; J.R. Biersmith: Oh,
that's a good question.

00:49:20.100 --> 00:49:23.430
I left all of that out.

00:49:23.430 --> 00:49:27.490
That whole part, all that struggle.

00:49:27.490 --> 00:49:33.870
I did, I worked on a project
when I first moved to LA,

00:49:33.870 --> 00:49:39.580
and then I got to, I did a lot
of, when that project was over

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:43.580
and I went to Tahiti, I spent
that next six months kind of just

00:49:43.580 --> 00:49:47.290
on surviving on the
money that I had saved.

00:49:47.290 --> 00:49:50.450 position:56%
And then I did a bunch of freelance,

00:49:50.450 --> 00:49:52.240
like some random freelance
projects just

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:55.000
to get some supplemental
income, and --

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.760
but this has really been
my life for three years.

00:49:57.760 --> 00:50:02.570
And it's been my life because
it's so incredibly complicated.

00:50:02.570 --> 00:50:04.790
I mean, in the middle of
night, you're calling Ethiopia,

00:50:04.790 --> 00:50:08.240
asking for footage of one game.

00:50:08.240 --> 00:50:10.960
Like I wasn't even sure if I
was going to use it in the film,

00:50:10.960 --> 00:50:13.160
and I had to track down a
journalist, figure out how

00:50:13.160 --> 00:50:16.030
to get a hold of the guy that might
have the footage that, you know,

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:19.930
holds it, you know, for the
dictatorship that's in charge

00:50:19.930 --> 00:50:25.230
of media that like chooses to
license things, so the journey

00:50:25.230 --> 00:50:30.350 position:56%
of trying to make this was just that
every single turn felt impossible.

00:50:30.350 --> 00:50:33.740
And that's why I extended way
longer than I ever expected.

00:50:33.740 --> 00:50:37.470
So after I went to Somalia,
we did a Kickstarter campaign,

00:50:37.470 --> 00:50:40.860
and we got $39,000 on
the Kickstarter campaign.

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:42.160
That was tough.

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:45.130
Like I thought I'd just send some
social media emails around, like,

00:50:45.130 --> 00:50:47.350
"Hey, if you like what
we're doing, give us $10."

00:50:47.350 --> 00:50:49.330
You know? Nobody was giving $10.

00:50:49.330 --> 00:50:51.410
Like, they were sharing
it like crazy, like,

00:50:51.410 --> 00:50:52.710
"Oh, this is super moving!"

00:50:52.710 --> 00:50:54.030
But nobody was giving money.

00:50:54.030 --> 00:50:55.940
Like I thought it would
just roll, but it didn't.

00:50:55.940 --> 00:50:57.470
Like it didn't just roll.

00:50:57.470 --> 00:51:00.200
I made a lot of phone calls,
and thankfully to my sister,

00:51:00.200 --> 00:51:03.100
my brother-in-law, they started
calling friends and saying,

00:51:03.100 --> 00:51:04.400
"Are you in for this amount?"

00:51:04.400 --> 00:51:05.700
"Are you in for this amount?"

00:51:05.700 --> 00:51:08.020
and all of a sudden,
you know, weeks went by,

00:51:08.020 --> 00:51:09.340
and we got that money
that we needed.

00:51:09.340 --> 00:51:12.400
And that helped a little bit,
but just going to Somalia

00:51:12.400 --> 00:51:14.340
for the five days that I was there,

00:51:14.340 --> 00:51:17.480
not to mention the countless other
filming trips that we did there,

00:51:17.480 --> 00:51:20.370
was like $10,000 just
for that five days.

00:51:20.370 --> 00:51:22.770
Because it's extremely expensive
to go out into the field

00:51:22.770 --> 00:51:25.490
because you have to have all these
security teams and everything else.

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:30.750
So that's how, and I borrowed a
lot of money; I owe a lot of money.

00:51:30.750 --> 00:51:33.840
That's the short answer
to the question.

00:51:33.840 --> 00:51:37.540
I just never, I just never dreamed
that it'd take as long as it did.

00:51:37.540 --> 00:51:39.800
And I think some people would say,
"Well, why did it take so long?"

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:42.840
Well, it took so long because
we spent a year trying to figure

00:51:42.840 --> 00:51:45.140
out like, literally every single
night trying to figure out,

00:51:45.140 --> 00:51:48.980
what do I do now to get
this kid out of Mogadishu?

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:51.590
And that's not a, like
a heroic thing.

00:51:51.590 --> 00:51:53.420
That's like being human.

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:56.080
Seriously, like when you meet these
kids, and you talk to these kids,

00:51:56.080 --> 00:51:58.910
and you hear, like, the
sacrifice that they're making,

00:51:58.910 --> 00:52:00.870
you don't have another choice.

00:52:00.870 --> 00:52:04.160
Like, it feels like your kid.

00:52:04.160 --> 00:52:06.820
